english:
  title: Preface to the Collection of Hundred Lineages Garments Poetry
  author: Jo Mun-bal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The 'Hundred Lineages Garments' style was first initiated by Wang Shu-wang of Tai-yuan, and later continued and developed by such masters as Huang Shan-gu and their peers. Observing its method: each poem plucks a single line from the ancients, weaves them together, and crafts anew a singular composition—the language and meaning blend so seamlessly that it appears wholly original. For human talent to reach such heights is rare even among the ancients, yet we find it flourishing in our own time.

    Master Lin Wei-cheng of Hsiang-yang possessed an acute and nimble nature. Whatever composition passed before his eyes and ears would immediately lodge in his memory, not a single word forgotten. Thus he prided himself on his prodigious recall. Throughout his life's writings, he frequently emulated Wang's method. When his brush danced upon the page, the masters—Shen Yo, Song Zhi-wen, Zhang Yue, Su Ting, Han Yu, Zhang Ji, Liu Yu-xi, and Bai Ju-yi—seemed to dwell within his breast, pouring forth lines at will. He shattered the rigid formations of the pedantic and captured the chieftains of ornate artifice; all their banners toppled and their ranks scattered. Such was his mastery. He prized swiftness over slowness, for generally those who wield the brush through patient monthly searching and daily refinement, when fortune grants them a fine piece, call it skillful—yet such laborious craft cannot compare to the achievements of swift roughness.

    After Master Lin passed the examinations and rose to the position of Rector of the National University, moving through palace halls and journeying to distant regions, whenever he encountered ancient and modern inscribed verses, he would instantly fashion matching rhymes—all infused with celestial inspiration. Consider such lines as: "The setting sun glows redder than embers; fallen flowers shine bright as silver," or "Mist-kissed layered peaks gleam as if carved by a blade; the river flows clear as unrolled silk." These truly exemplify the meditation of the brush's tip, playing freely and unfettered. Yet heaven granted him not the years; he passed into the long darkness, and his poems were largely lost—nine in ten vanished from the world. Those who knew him could not satisfy their longing.

    At this time, Prime Minister Choe Yu of Cheongha, a gentleman devoted to good works, gathered the scattered remnants of his surviving verses—several pieces in all. As he recited them, his heart grew melancholy, like one sipping sweet wine then having the cup withdrawn, hearing beautiful music but unable to hear it to its close. He summoned me and said: "These words are precious as gold and jade. Surely someone will treasure them for posterity. You must compose a preface and prevent such brilliance from being buried in earth." His request was most earnest. How could I refuse on grounds of meager talent? So I accepted and reviewed the work several times. Where lines were repeated, I prepared to delete them, but the Minister said: "Bai Ju-yi was a great poet, yet in his collected works the phrase 'the empty wall has excess' appears in two places. The ancient anthologies, even when containing such repetitions, did not deem it harmful to their meaning." Thus we kept them all, divided the work into three scrolls, and borrowed Huang Shan-gu's phrase to title it 'Collection of Hundred Lineages Garments,' that it might endure. Alas! The Minister, occupied with the state's governance and the people's welfare, has little leisure for such matters, yet his reverence for learned men runs so deep and earnest that he has cherished Master Lin's surviving work thus. If the departed have awareness, surely the Master's spirit feels grateful.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Hundred Lineages Garments' (百家衣) is a poetic form where lines from classical masters are woven together to create new compositions, much like garments made from patches of fine cloth.
  - key: ''
    value: Lin Wei-cheng held the position of Rector (祭酒) of the National University (國子監), a significant honor in the Joseon administrative system.
  - key: ''
    value: The eight masters mentioned—Shen Yo, Song Zhi-wen, Zhang Yue, Su Ting, Han Yu, Zhang Ji, Liu Yu-xi, and Bai Ju-yi—represent the pinnacle of Chinese poetic achievement across different periods.
  - key: ''
    value: The repeated line from Bai Ju-yi cited by Minister Choe demonstrates that even the greatest poets use repetition without compromising their work's integrity.
